\begin{abstract}
Automated glaucoma screening models trained on Western fundus datasets
are widely assumed to degrade substantially on Indian retinal images due
to phenotypic and acquisition-induced domain shifts.  We revisit this
assumption using a DINOv3 ViT-Large foundation model (303M parameters)
fine-tuned on the Western AIROGS dataset ($n{=}9{,}540$) and evaluated
on the Indian Ch\'{a}k\c{s}u dataset ($n{=}336$ test images; 15.2\%
glaucoma prevalence).  Contrary to prior expectations, the source model
alone achieves an AUROC of \textbf{0.846}, closing 85\% of the gap to
the in-domain supervised oracle (0.900)---without any adaptation.  This
finding establishes that DINOv3 features generalise cross-ethnically to
a degree not previously documented in fundus-image analysis.
We present \textbf{Netra-Adapt}, a Source-Free Domain Adaptation (SFDA)
framework built on \textbf{MixEnt-Adapt}: an uncertainty-guided
mechanism that partitions target samples by predictive entropy and
performs AdaIN-style feature calibration between confident and uncertain
samples, driven by an Information Maximisation (IM) objective.  A
systematic analysis reveals that standard IM objectives, when applied
to class-imbalanced medical datasets (86\% Normal in Ch\'{a}k\c{s}u),
are susceptible to deterministic mode collapse: the diversity
maximisation term applied over the full batch creates an implicit bias
that drives uncertain predictions towards the minority class, whereupon
entropy minimisation locks in the erroneous predictions.  We formally
characterise this failure mode and propose three targeted corrections---
scope-restricted diversity maximisation, class-prior regularisation,
and removal of pseudo-labelling---that together prevent collapse.
These results establish a strong baseline for cross-ethnic glaucoma
screening and identify critical loss-design constraints for SFDA under
clinical class imbalance.
\end{abstract}

