\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}

Glaucoma is the second leading cause of irreversible blindness
worldwide, affecting over 76 million people globally
\cite{tham2014global}.  Early detection through regular screening is
critical for preventing vision loss, yet access to specialist
ophthalmologists remains limited in many regions.  Automated screening
systems based on deep-learning analysis of fundus photographs have
shown promising results in controlled settings \cite{li2018efficacy},
but their deployment across diverse populations remains a significant
challenge.

A critical barrier to equitable deployment is the
\emph{cross-ethnic domain shift} between training and target
populations.  Models trained predominantly on Western datasets, such as
AIROGS \cite{vermeer2024airogs}, exhibit substantial performance
degradation when evaluated on Indian retinal images from the
Ch\'{a}k\c{s}u dataset \cite{kumar2023chakshu}.  This degradation stems
from two primary sources of domain shift.
\textit{Phenotypic differences}: Indian retinas exhibit higher melanin
pigmentation, resulting in a darker fundus appearance and altered
contrast characteristics \cite{rajesh2025rps}.
\textit{Acquisition differences}: Western datasets use standardised
desktop fundus cameras, whereas Indian datasets employ handheld devices
(Remidio, Forus, Bosch) with variable illumination, sharpness, and
colour profiles.

The practical deployment of glaucoma screening systems is further
constrained by realistic clinical requirements.  Privacy regulations
such as GDPR and HIPAA restrict the sharing of patient data, meaning
that source training data cannot be accessed during adaptation.
Additionally, obtaining diagnostic labels for target-domain images
requires expert ophthalmologist annotation, making supervised
fine-tuning prohibitively expensive.  These constraints define the
\emph{Source-Free Domain Adaptation} (SFDA) setting, where adaptation
must proceed using only unlabelled target data without access to source
data or target labels.

We present \textbf{Netra-Adapt}, a novel SFDA framework for
cross-ethnic glaucoma screening built on three key insights.
First, self-supervised Vision Transformers such as DINOv3
\cite{chen2026dinov3medical} learn shape-based representations that are
inherently more robust to pigmentation variations than texture-based
CNN features.  Second, test-time feature calibration can align the
statistical distributions of source and target domains without
requiring retraining.  Third, uncertainty-guided adaptation---which
focuses computational resources on samples with high prediction
entropy---is more effective than uniform adaptation.

The core technical contribution of Netra-Adapt is
\textbf{MixEnt-Adapt}, a mechanism that calibrates features through
three steps: (1) partitioning target samples into confident and
uncertain groups based on predictive entropy; (2) extracting mean and
variance statistics from token embeddings; and (3) applying AdaIN-style
normalisation to align uncertain samples with the distribution of
confident samples.  Adaptation is driven by the Information
Maximisation (IM) loss, which encourages confident predictions while
maintaining class diversity.

Our experiments on the AIROGS$\to$Ch\'{a}k\c{s}u benchmark yield two
central results.  First, the DINOv3 source model achieves an AUROC of
\textbf{0.846} on Indian retinal images without any adaptation, compared
to 0.414 for the untuned backbone and 0.900 for the supervised oracle.
This demonstrates that foundation model features generalise
cross-ethnically far more robustly than CNN-based models reported in
prior literature.  Second, we identify and characterise a
previously-undocumented failure mode of IM-based SFDA under clinical
class imbalance, provide a formal analysis, and propose three targeted
corrections that produce a stable adaptation procedure.

