\section{Related Work}
\label{sec:related}

\subsection{Glaucoma Detection with Deep Learning}

Deep-learning approaches for glaucoma detection from fundus images have
evolved through several paradigms.  Early work employed convolutional
neural networks (CNNs) such as ResNet and DenseNet for direct
classification \cite{zedan2023survey}.  Subsequent approaches adopted
segmentation-based pipelines, using U-Net architectures to segment the
optic disc and cup, from which the cup-to-disc ratio (CDR)---a key
clinical indicator---is computed \cite{shinde2021glaucoma}.  More
recently, Vision Transformers (ViTs) have been applied to capture
global contextual relationships in fundus images
\cite{manzari2023medvit}.  Despite these advances, most studies assume
independent and identically distributed (i.i.d.) training and test
data; the challenge of cross-ethnic generalisation, where training and
test populations differ systematically in phenotypic characteristics,
remains underexplored.

\subsection{Domain Adaptation for Medical Imaging}

Domain adaptation techniques aim to improve model performance on target
domains that differ from the training domain.  Supervised Domain
Adaptation (SDA) assumes access to labelled target data
\cite{guan2021survey}, which is unrealistic for medical applications
where expert annotation is expensive.  Unsupervised Domain Adaptation
(UDA) relaxes this to unlabelled target data but typically requires
access to source data during adaptation \cite{wilson2020survey},
violating privacy constraints.

Source-Free Domain Adaptation (SFDA) addresses both limitations by
adapting a pre-trained source model to an unlabelled target domain
without accessing source data.  SHOT \cite{liang2020shot} established
the foundation for SFDA through IM loss combined with pseudo-labelling.
Subsequent work has explored Fourier-style mining for medical
segmentation \cite{yang20223daim}, prototype-based clustering
\cite{li2024sfda}, and autonomous information filtering
\cite{li2025aifsfda}.  However, SFDA for cross-ethnic medical imaging,
where domain shift is driven by biological and acquisition factors,
remains largely unexplored.

\subsection{Test-Time Adaptation}

Test-Time Adaptation (TTA) methods update model parameters during
inference to adapt to distribution shifts.  Tent \cite{wang2020tent}
introduced entropy minimisation with batch normalisation updates,
demonstrating that test-time calibration can recover performance lost
to domain shift.  Subsequent work has addressed stability concerns
\cite{niu2023stabletta}, developed single-sample variants
\cite{goyal2022tta}, and applied graph-guided adaptation specifically
for glaucoma detection \cite{gtta2024}.  Most TTA methods focus on CNN
architectures and update batch normalisation statistics; adaptation of
Vision Transformers at the token level remains less explored.

\subsection{Fairness and Cross-Ethnic Generalisation}

Recent work has highlighted the importance of fairness in medical AI
systems.  FairDomain \cite{fairdomain2024} demonstrated that domain
shift exacerbates performance disparities across demographic groups.
In ophthalmology, the Retinal Pigment Score (RPS) \cite{rajesh2025rps}
provides a continuous metric for quantifying fundus pigmentation,
revealing substantial variation within and across ethnic groups.
Burlina et al.\ \cite{burlina2021bias} showed that deep-learning models
for retinal diagnostics exhibit bias related to fundus pigmentation.
These findings underscore the need for domain adaptation methods that
explicitly address phenotypic variation.

\subsection{Self-Supervised Learning for Medical Imaging}

Self-supervised learning has emerged as a powerful paradigm for learning
representations without labelled data.  DINO and DINOv2
\cite{caron2021dino} learn through self-distillation, producing Vision
Transformers that capture shape-based features rather than texture.
Recent evaluation on medical imaging tasks \cite{chen2026dinov3medical}
confirms that DINOv3 provides strong zero-shot performance and that
shape-based features are more robust to domain variations than
supervised CNN features.  This motivates our choice of DINOv3 as the
backbone for Netra-Adapt.

