\section{Methodology}
\label{sec:method}

\subsection{Problem Formulation}
\label{sec:formulation}

We consider the Source-Free Domain Adaptation setting with three
components.  The \textbf{source domain}
$\mathcal{D}_S = \{(x_i^s, y_i^s)\}_{i=1}^{n_s}$ consists of Western
fundus images with binary diagnostic labels (Normal / Glaucoma).  The
\textbf{target domain}
$\mathcal{D}_T = \{x_i^t\}_{i=1}^{n_t}$ consists of Indian fundus
images without labels.  The \textbf{source model} $f_\theta$ is
pre-trained on $\mathcal{D}_S$ with parameters~$\theta$.

The goal is to adapt $f_\theta$ to perform well on $\mathcal{D}_T$
under three constraints: (i) source data $\mathcal{D}_S$ is
inaccessible during adaptation; (ii) target labels are unavailable;
and (iii) no supervised retraining on $\mathcal{D}_T$ is performed.

\subsection{Netra-Adapt Architecture}
\label{sec:architecture}

Netra-Adapt employs a DINOv3 ViT-L/16 backbone pre-trained on natural
images as its foundation.  The full model contains 303M parameters, of
which only the last two transformer blocks and the classification head
(25M parameters; 8.3\% of the total) are left trainable during
adaptation.  The classification head is a linear projection from 1024
dimensions to two output classes.  Freezing the majority of the
backbone preserves the shape-based representations learned through
self-supervised pre-training, while the trainable components enable
task-specific adaptation.

\subsection{MixEnt-Adapt: Uncertainty-Guided Feature Calibration}
\label{sec:mixent}

The core of Netra-Adapt is MixEnt-Adapt, a three-step mechanism for
calibrating features at test time.

\paragraph{Step 1: Entropy-Based Sample Partitioning.}
For each target sample $x$ in a batch, we compute the predictive
entropy:
\begin{equation}
    H(x) = -\sum_{c \in \{0,1\}} p(c|x)\log p(c|x),
    \label{eq:entropy}
\end{equation}
where $p(c|x)$ is the model's predicted probability for class $c$.
The batch is partitioned as
\begin{align}
    \mathcal{C} &= \{x : H(x) < \tau\} \quad \text{(confident samples)},
    \label{eq:confident}\\
    \mathcal{U} &= \{x : H(x) \geq \tau\} \quad \text{(uncertain samples)},
    \label{eq:uncertain}
\end{align}
where $\tau$ is an entropy threshold.  We evaluate three strategies for
setting $\tau$: (1) a fixed value; (2) an adaptive percentile-based
threshold ($\tau = \mathrm{median}(\{H(x_i)\})$); and (3) a learnable
parameter optimised during adaptation.

\paragraph{Step 2: Feature Statistics Extraction.}
For ViT token embeddings $z \in \mathbb{R}^{N \times d}$, where $N$ is
the number of tokens and $d$ is the embedding dimension, we compute
\begin{align}
    \mu(z) &= \frac{1}{N}\sum_{i=1}^{N} z_i,
    \label{eq:mu}\\
    \sigma(z) &= \sqrt{\frac{1}{N}\sum_{i=1}^{N}
                 \bigl(z_i - \mu(z)\bigr)^2 + \varepsilon}.
    \label{eq:sigma}
\end{align}
These statistics are computed separately for confident samples
($\mu_c,\,\sigma_c$) and uncertain samples ($\mu_u,\,\sigma_u$).

\paragraph{Step 3: AdaIN-Style Feature Injection.}
For each uncertain sample $z_u \in \mathcal{U}$, we apply adaptive
instance normalisation to align its statistics with those of the
confident samples:
\begin{equation}
    z_{\mathrm{adapted}} = \sigma_c \cdot
      \frac{z_u - \mu_u}{\sigma_u} + \mu_c.
    \label{eq:adain}
\end{equation}
This operation removes the ``uncertain style'' (characterised by
$\mu_u,\sigma_u$) and injects the ``confident style'' (characterised
by $\mu_c,\sigma_c$), effectively aligning uncertain samples with the
distribution of samples on which the model predicts confidently.
We additionally introduce a mixing parameter $\alpha \in [0,1]$ to
control adaptation strength:
\begin{equation}
    z_{\mathrm{final}} = \alpha \cdot z_{\mathrm{adapted}}
                       + (1-\alpha) \cdot z_u,
    \label{eq:mix}
\end{equation}
where $\alpha$ can be fixed, set proportionally to certainty
($\alpha = 1 - H(x)/H_{\max}$), or learned.

\subsection{Information Maximisation Loss}
\label{sec:imloss}

Since target labels are unavailable, adaptation is driven by the
Information Maximisation (IM) loss:
\begin{equation}
    \mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{IM}} = \mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{ent}}
                               - \lambda\,\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{div}},
    \label{eq:imloss}
\end{equation}
where the \textbf{entropy minimisation} term
$\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{ent}} = -\tfrac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\sum_{c}
p(c|x_i)\log p(c|x_i)$
encourages confident predictions, and the \textbf{diversity
maximisation} term
$\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{div}} = \sum_{c}\hat{p}(c)\log\hat{p}(c)$,
with marginal class distribution
$\hat{p}(c) = \tfrac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n}p(c|x_i)$,
prevents collapse to a single class.
The hyperparameter $\lambda$ balances these two objectives and is
tuned on a held-out validation set.

\subsection{Enhancements}
\label{sec:enhancements}

\paragraph{Temperature Scaling for Calibration.}
To improve model calibration, we apply temperature scaling to the
logits before computing softmax probabilities:
\begin{equation}
    p'(c|x) = \mathrm{softmax}\!\left(\frac{z(x)}{T}\right),
    \label{eq:temp}
\end{equation}
where $T > 1$ reduces overconfidence.  The optimal temperature is
determined by minimising Expected Calibration Error (ECE) on the
validation set.

\paragraph{Camera-Aware Adaptation.}
The Ch\'{a}k\c{s}u dataset contains images from three handheld cameras
with different resolutions: Remidio ($2448 \times 3264$ px), Forus
($2048 \times 1536$ px), and Bosch ($1920 \times 1440$ px).  Camera
identity is inferred automatically from image dimensions.  During
adaptation, the system maintains camera-specific feature statistics and
performs camera-conditional feature alignment, reducing intra-domain
heterogeneity within the target dataset.

\subsection{Training Procedure}
\label{sec:training}

Algorithm~\ref{alg:netraadapt} summarises the full Netra-Adapt
adaptation procedure.

\begin{algorithm}[t]
\caption{Netra-Adapt Adaptation}
\label{alg:netraadapt}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\Require Source model $f_\theta$; unlabelled target data $\mathcal{D}_T$;
         entropy threshold $\tau$; diversity weight $\lambda$
\For{each adaptation epoch}
    \For{each batch $\mathcal{B} \subset \mathcal{D}_T$}
        \State Compute token features: $Z = \mathrm{Backbone}(\mathcal{B})$
        \State Compute predictions: $P = \mathrm{Head}(Z)$
        \State Compute per-sample entropy: $H = -\sum_c P\log P$
        \State Partition: $\mathcal{C} \leftarrow \{x : H(x)<\tau\}$;\;
               $\mathcal{U} \leftarrow \{x : H(x)\geq\tau\}$
        \State Compute statistics $(\mu_c,\sigma_c)$ from $Z_{\mathcal{C}}$
               and $(\mu_u,\sigma_u)$ from $Z_{\mathcal{U}}$
        \State Apply AdaIN: $Z_{\mathrm{adapted}} \leftarrow
               \sigma_c\,\frac{Z_{\mathcal{U}}-\mu_u}{\sigma_u}+\mu_c$
        \State Mix: $Z_{\mathrm{final}} \leftarrow
               \alpha\,Z_{\mathrm{adapted}} + (1-\alpha)\,Z_{\mathcal{U}}$
        \State Compute IM loss: $\mathcal{L} =
               \mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{ent}} - \lambda\,\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{div}}$
        \State Update trainable parameters:
               $\theta_{\mathrm{tr}} \leftarrow
                \theta_{\mathrm{tr}} - \eta\nabla_{\theta_{\mathrm{tr}}}\mathcal{L}$
    \EndFor
\EndFor
\State \Return Adapted model $f_{\theta'}$
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

