\section{Experimental Setup}
\label{sec:experiments}

\subsection{Datasets}
\label{sec:datasets}

\paragraph{Source: AIROGS.}
The AIROGS (AI for RObust Glaucoma Screening) dataset
\cite{vermeer2024airogs} comprises fundus images from the EyePACS
screening network, consisting of a training split of 7,632 images and a
test split of 1,908 images drawn predominantly from a Western
population captured with standardised desktop fundus cameras.  Labels
are Normal, Glaucoma, or Ungradable; ungradable images are excluded from
all experiments.  All images are resized to $512\times512$ pixels for
model input.

\paragraph{Target: Ch\'{a}k\c{s}u.}
Ch\'{a}k\c{s}u \cite{kumar2023chakshu} is the largest publicly
available Indian-ethnicity glaucoma fundus dataset with expert
majority-vote annotations, comprising 1,345 images in total.  The
official labelled partition contains 1,009 training images and 336 test
images; the test set comprises 285 Normal and 51 Glaucoma cases
(84.8\% / 15.2\%), reflecting realistic clinical class imbalance.
Images were acquired with three handheld devices: Remidio
Fundus-on-Phone (1,074 images, $2448\!\times\!3264$\,px; 79.9\%),
Forus 3Nethra Classic (126 images, $2048\!\times\!1536$\,px; 9.4\%),
and Bosch handheld camera (145 images, $1920\!\times\!1440$\,px;
10.8\%).  Relative to AIROGS, the dataset exhibits both phenotypic shift
(higher melanin pigmentation, darker fundus appearance) and acquisition
shift (variable illumination, sharpness, and colour profiles across
three physically distinct camera systems).  The 1,009 training images
are used \emph{unlabelled} for SFDA adaptation; the 336 test images
with ground-truth labels are held out for final evaluation only and are
never used during adaptation.

\subsection{Evaluation Metrics}
\label{sec:metrics}

Performance is assessed using the following metrics: AUROC (area under
the receiver operating characteristic curve; primary metric), overall
classification Accuracy, Sensitivity (true positive rate), Specificity
(true negative rate), F1-Score (harmonic mean of precision and recall),
ECE (Expected Calibration Error), and Brier Score (mean squared error
of probabilistic predictions).

\subsection{Baselines}
\label{sec:baselines}

We compare Netra-Adapt against four baselines spanning training-free,
supervised, and SFDA approaches.
\textbf{RAG} is a training-free $k$-nearest-neighbour classifier that
assigns target images labels by majority vote over their closest source
neighbours in feature space; we evaluate $k \in \{5, 10, 20, 50\}$
and report the best.
\textbf{Frozen DINO} applies the pre-trained DINOv3 model to
Ch\'{a}k\c{s}u without any adaptation, serving as a zero-shot
reference.
\textbf{SFT (Oracle)} fine-tunes the model directly on the labelled
Ch\'{a}k\c{s}u training split and represents an approximate upper
bound under the unrealistic assumption that labelled target data are
available.
\textbf{SHOT} \cite{liang2020shot} is the state-of-the-art SFDA
baseline employing IM loss with pseudo-labelling.

\subsection{Implementation Details}
\label{sec:implementation}

The backbone is DINOv3 ViT-L/16
(\texttt{facebook/dinov3-vitl16-pretrain-lvd1689m}) with 303M
parameters.

\textbf{Phase A -- Source Training.} The source model is trained on
AIROGS using AdamW optimisation with a backbone learning rate of
$10^{-5}$, a head learning rate of $10^{-3}$, a batch size of~48 with
WeightedRandomSampler, and up to 60 epochs with early stopping
(patience~10).  The source AUROC on the AIROGS test set (held-out)
is 0.981, confirming correct training.

\textbf{Phase B -- Target Adaptation (Netra-Adapt / MixEnt-Adapt).}
Adaptation uses AdamW with a backbone learning rate of
$5\!\times\!10^{-6}$, a head learning rate of $5\!\times\!10^{-4}$,
a batch size of~32 with dual augmentation (weak and strong views per
image), and up to 50 epochs with early stopping (patience~12).  The
entropy threshold is set adaptively (batch-level median).  Information
Maximisation is applied over the uncertain sample pool only
($\lambda_{\mathrm{div}} = 1.0$); a class-prior regularisation term
$\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{bal}} = \mathrm{KL}(\bar{p}\,\|\,[0.85, 0.15])$
with weight 1.0 constrains the batch marginal.  A ProtoStyleBank
($K{=}256$ per class) accumulates style statistics across batches;
a 3-epoch warmup phase seeds the bank before gradient updates begin.
Gradient clipping (max norm 1.0) and CosineAnnealingLR are applied
throughout.  All experiments use fixed random seeds.

