\section{Discussion}
\label{sec:discussion}

\subsection{Why the Source Model is Surprisingly Strong}

The source model achieves AUROC 0.846 on Indian retinal images without
any adaptation.  Three factors explain this transferability.

\textit{Shape-biased representations.}  DINOv3 learns through
self-supervised distillation over diverse natural images, favouring
shape over texture~\cite{caron2021dino}.  Glaucoma diagnosis is
fundamentally a shape task --- cup-to-disc ratio, rim thinning, and
nerve fibre layer defects are the primary indicators --- and these
morphological signals are preserved across ethnicities and device types.

\textit{Large, balanced source training.}  AIROGS provides 9,540
images at 50\% glaucoma prevalence.  A balanced, large-scale training
set produces a well-calibrated head that transfers reliably even when
target prevalence (15.2\%) differs substantially from the training
distribution.

\textit{Global receptive field.}  The ViT-L architecture captures the
entire optic disc context in a single forward pass, reducing dependence
on local texture statistics that vary across devices.

These results challenge the widespread assumption that domain shift is
the primary bottleneck for cross-ethnic medical AI.  For DINOv3-scale
foundation models, the 5.4-point gap to oracle may reflect irreducible
phenotypic variation more than remediable domain mismatch.

\subsection{Why RAG Failed}

The RAG baseline achieved near-random performance (AUROC 0.509),
demonstrating that feature-space similarity alone cannot overcome
cross-ethnic domain shift.  The domain shift displaces embeddings such
that nearest neighbours in the Western source database do not correspond
to pathologically similar images in the target domain.  RAG prioritises
visual similarity (colour, contrast, brightness) over pathological
structure (optic disc morphology), and the target class imbalance
(85\% Normal) causes the retrieval system to increasingly favour the
majority class as $k$ grows.  These findings confirm that
retrieval-based approaches are insufficient for cross-ethnic medical
imaging.

\subsection{IM Loss Instability Under Class Imbalance}

The Run-6 collapse reveals a broader issue with IM-based SFDA that has
not been explicitly documented for medical imaging.  The formal
analysis in \S\ref{sec:imloss_collapse} shows that the standard
diversity term $-\mathcal{H}(\mathbb{E}[p])$, applied over a full
batch with $\geq\!70\%$ majority-class prevalence, creates a
class-imbalance-dependent bias that drives the minority class
representation upward.  Clinical glaucoma datasets universally exhibit
10--25\% glaucoma prevalence --- precisely the regime where this
instability arises.  The failure mode is therefore likely to affect any
SFDA method using the standard IM objective in medical contexts without
explicit correction.

The three proposed corrections (Run-7) directly address both causal
mechanisms.  Whether they yield a measurable AUROC improvement over the
already-strong source model (0.846) is an empirical question currently
under evaluation.

\subsection{Limitations}

Four main limitations apply.  (i)~Batch processing is required;
single-sample adaptation remains unsupported.  (ii)~The 5.4-point
oracle gap may be partially irreducible phenotypic variation.
(iii)~Ablation results are pending completion of stable adaptation.
(iv)~The framework is limited to binary glaucoma screening; multi-stage
grading is left for future work.

\subsection{Future Work}

Immediate next steps are completing Run-7 evaluation and ablating each
MixEnt-Adapt component.  Longer-term directions include: single-sample
TTA variants; multi-class glaucoma grading; prospective clinical
validation; and evaluation on additional ethnic populations (Southeast
Asian, African) to assess broader cross-ethnic generalisability.

