\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}

We have presented Netra-Adapt, a Source-Free Domain Adaptation framework
for cross-ethnic glaucoma screening built on MixEnt-Adapt---an
uncertainty-guided feature calibration mechanism using AdaIN-style
normalisation driven by an Information Maximisation objective.  Two
central findings emerge from this work.

First, a DINOv3 source model trained solely on Western AIROGS data
achieves an AUROC of \textbf{0.846} on Indian Ch\'{a}k\c{s}u retinal
images, closing 85\% of the gap to the in-domain supervised oracle
(0.900) without any adaptation.  This establishes that DINOv3
features transfer cross-ethnically far more robustly than previously
documented in fundus-image analysis, and constitutes the strongest
published zero-adaptation cross-ethnic glaucoma screening result to date.

Second, the standard IM objective applied to a class-imbalanced target
domain (86\% Normal) causes deterministic mode collapse.  We formally
characterise this failure as arising from a mismatch between the scopes
of $\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{ent}}$ and $\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{div}}$,
compounded by miscalibrated pseudo-labels under domain shift.  Three
targeted corrections prevent collapse and constitute a stable SFDA
procedure for class-imbalanced medical datasets.

Taken together, these results establish a strong foundation model
baseline for cross-ethnic glaucoma screening and identify critical
loss-design principles for SFDA under clinical class imbalance, with
implications extending beyond ophthalmology to any medical SFDA
application with imbalanced labels.

